<tr><td class='easySpoilerRow' colspan='2' style=''><div id='spoilerDiv605e8001' class='easySpoilerSpoils'  style='display:none; white-space:wrap; overflow:auto; vertical-align:middle;'>
</p>
<p>The only way to partition the 18 shots into 3 equal sets of 6 is:</p>
<p>25, 20, 20, 3, 2, 1<br />
25, 20, 10, 10, 5, 1<br />
50, 10, 5, 3, 2, 1</p>
<p>The first row must be Andryusha&#8217;s, since it&#8217;s the only one that contains two numbers totaling 22.</p>
<p>The score 3 appears only in the first and third rows, so the third must be Volodya&#8217;s. Thus he hit the bullseye.</p>
<p>From Boris Kordemsky&#8217;s <a href="https://archive.org/details/boris-a.-kordemsky-the-moscow-puzzles-1972/page/110/mode/2up"><em>The Moscow Puzzles</em></a>, 1956.</p>
<p>
